text.tspan: Abstract
Introduction
Methods
Results & Discussion
Building on previous research in our lab and other laboratories, we have
developped a mixed SINDy framework that integrates function catalogs from
multiple paradigms:
- Lagrangian mechanics
- Newton equation
- Other models (e.g., symmetric fluid forces on joints)
To evaluate the efficiency of this new method, we conducted 15 experiments on
each of the following three systems:
Across these 45 experiments, we tested both classical SINDy1 and the mixed
classical/Lagrangian SINDy2 using two different sparse regression algorithms:
coordinate descent and recursive hard-thresholding.
In total, considering 45 experiments × 4 method-parameter combinations, we
retrieved the system dynamics under four noise levels, resulting in a batch of 720
SINDy experiments.
During the testing phase, we generated new trajectories for both the real system
and the retrieved system, evaluating their deviation from the ideal trajectory
using the RMSE metric (Root Mean Square Error of the trajectory).

text.tspan: The heart of Sparse Identification of Nonlinear Dynamics is to retrieve system
dynamic equations from data :
1. Define a catalog of functions that could appear in the system's Lagrangian or
Newton equations.
2. Collect experimental data.
3. Identify the significant functions governing the system using LASSO
regression (sparse linear regression).
4. Validate the retrieved dynamics
Research on the SINDy algorithm aims to enhance noise resilience and improve
the accuracy of system dynamics retrieval.
1 : In order to make a fair comparison the classical SINDy catalog has been reduced to have the same number of function as the
more compact Lagrangian SINDy
2 : Catalog only composed of lagrangian function has been discarded because system are subject to friction forces that are not
lagrangian compatible
The new mixed method has proven to be more noise-resillient while
simultaneously achieving better performance in low-noise experiments.
Meanwhile, the hard-threshold algorithm has outperformed the previously used
coordinate descent algorithm in the laboratory.
